  * xharbour/contrib/libmisc/dates2.c
  * xharbour/contrib/rdd_ads/adsfunc.c
  * xharbour/contrib/xwt/src/xwt_gtk/xwt_gtk_calendar.c
  * xharbour/source/clipsamp/date.c
  * xharbour/source/tip/base64x.c
  * xharbour/source/tip/utils.c
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT

  * xharbour/contrib/rdd_ads/ads1.c
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT
    + added adsRecInfo() - Brian please look at it - I cannot test
      this code

  * xharbour/include/hbapi.h
  * xharbour/include/hbapiitm.h
    - removed HB_IT_LONGLONG item
    + added HB_IT_NUMINT/HB_IS_NUMINT(p) macros as in Harbour
      (the HB_IT_NUMERINT/HB_IS_NUMBER_INT(p) left for compatibility)
    + added(changed) hb_parnint()/hb_retnint()/hb_retnintlen()/hb_stornint()/
      hb_itemPutNInt()/hb_itemPutNIntLen()/hb_itemGetNInt()/hb_arrayGetNInt()
      functions which operates on HB_LONG - maximum supported integer but
      internally chose the optimal HB_ITEM type for storing the value if
      possible
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT
    + added [ double hb_numInt(double) ] function which makes similar
      hack to hb_numRound() 'fixating' the results
    * hb_strValInt() now returns HB_LONG
    ! reverted hb_strVal( szText, ... ) to
      hb_strVal( const char * szText, ULONG ulLen );
      This modification caused incompatibilities with 3-rd party libs and
      even with some core xHarbour code
    + added new functions for string to number conversions - each of
      them use the same internal function to keep the same FL results
      in different conversions as hb_numRound()/hb_numInt() and return
      the BOOL value which informs about type of results (TRUE-double,
      FALSE-HB_LONG) stored in one of argument passed by reference -
      it's necessary for eliminating INT64<->double conversions which
      can INT64 number.

  * xharbour/include/hbapicdp.h
    + added #define hb_cdp_page s_cdpage
    + added IT codepages

  * xharbour/include/hbapifs.h
    * changed the size member of HB_FFIND from LONGLONG to HB_FOFFSET

  * xharbour/include/hbcomp.h
    * changed the argument in hb_compGenPushLong() to HB_LONG

  * xharbour/include/hbdate.h
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT

  * xharbour/include/hbdbf.h
    - removed pack() for OS/2 and __EMX__ - it should be no more pack
      dependent structure in RDD - if I'm wrong then I should fix the
      code instead of adding the pack commands

  * xharbour/include/hbdefs.h
    + added definitions and macros for 64bit platforms.
    + added macros for integer range checking
    + added macros for length setting in numeric ITEMs
    + added macros for limiting the range of integer numbers in PCODE
      for strict CLIPPER compatibility
    + added support for HB_STRICT_ALIGNMENT and HB_ALLOC_ALIGNMENT
      macros - some platforms like based on SPARC processors need it
    + added HB_PUT_PTR()/HB_GET_PTR() macros for platforms which needs
      strict alignment - they should be used instead of C casting in
      places like PCODE when we do not now the exact address alignment

  * xharbour/include/hbexprb.c
    * casting

  * xharbour/include/hbexprop.h
    * changed LONG to HB_LONG in asNum structure and hb_compExprNewLong()
      functions for 64bit support

  * xharbour/include/hbmacro.h
    * changed LONG to HB_LONG in hb_compGenPushLong()

  * xharbour/include/hbpcode.h
    + added new PCODE HB_P_PUSHLONGLONG

  * xharbour/include/hbapirdd.h
    * some modification still not enabled for future use

  * xharbour/include/hbrddfpt.h
    - removed some commented out definitions

  * xharbour/include/hbrddntx.h
    ! added NTX_MAX_TAGNAME to avoid buffer overflow and GPFs when
      long file names are used
    * changed variable length structure definitions to fixed one
      Now DBFNTX works on 64bit machines but it's still not endian free
      so the index files created on BE platforms are not binary compatible

  * xharbour/include/hbsetup.h
    * define HB_OS_BSD when HB_OS_DARWIN is set
    * define HB_OS_UNIX when HB_OS_SUNOS is set

  * xharbour/include/hbvm.h
    + hb_vmPushLongLong() now operates on HB_LONG
    - removed hb_vmPushNumInt()

  * xharbour/include/hbvmpub.h
    * HB_IT_LONG now use internaly HB_LONG C type
    - removed HB_IT_LONGLONG structures

  * xharbour/source/common/expropt1.c
  * xharbour/source/common/expropt2.c
    + added support for 64bit integers
    * modifications to operate on HB_LONG instead of LONG
    ! fixed the bad ITEM size in some optimizations
    * modifications to reduce when possible HB_LONG<->double conversions

  * xharbour/source/common/hbfsapi.c

  * xharbour/source/common/hbstr.c
    + added support for 64bit integers
    + added new functions for string to number conversions - each of
      them use the same internal function to keep the same FL results
      in different conversions as hb_numRound()/hb_numInt() and return
      the BOOL value which informs about type of results (TRUE-double,
      FALSE-HB_LONG) stored in one of argument passed by reference -
      it's necessary for eliminating INT64<->double conversions which
      can INT64 number.
    + added [ double hb_numInt(double) ] function which makes similar
      hack to hb_numRound() 'fixating' the results
    * grouped functions which converts string to number with the ones
      which make rounding to keep the same algorithm and be sure that
      they are compiled together with the same compiler switches

  * xharbour/source/common/hbver.c
    + added machine type to string returned by hb_verPlatform() in
      *nixes

  * xharbour/source/compiler/cmdcheck.c
    * casting

  * xharbour/source/compiler/harbour.c
  * xharbour/source/compiler/hbfix.c
  * xharbour/source/compiler/hbpcode.c
  * xharbour/source/compiler/genc.c
    + added support for 64bit integers
    * replaced all manual offset calculations with proper macros
    ! fixes for 64 bit platform where LONG is 64bit integer
    + added HB_GENC_FUNC( hb_p_pushlonglong )
    ! fixed bug in jump optimization (calculation of jump size) - fix
      borrowed from Harbour and was originally done by Ryszard - thanks
    * fixed yet another bug in jump optimization (updating new jump address)
    ! fixed memory leak in jump optimization with updating of

